25
00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:33.680
So without any further ado, I would like to introduce the

26
00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:34.560
first speaker.

27
00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:37.000
Let me see in the program.

28
00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:42.780
So the first speaker is Dr Steele,

29
00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:47.380
and the title is "The Genomic Landscape of Likely Human

30
00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:48.260
Pre-cancers."

31
00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:50.020
Thank you.

32
00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:58.820
Thank you for the opportunity to talk today.

33
00:01:59.140 --> 00:02:01.170
It's very fitting that the first

34
00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:06.500
talk of this session is on pre-cancers, moving into cancers later.

35
00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:10.521
And as such, I will be discussing the genomic landscape of likely human

36
00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:14.440
pre-cancers. I have no financial relationships to

37
00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:14.900
disclose

38
00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:19.580
. So first things first, what exactly is pre-cancer?

39
00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:23.740
Well, it represents an intermediate stage between normal tissues

40
00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:28.200
and invasive cancer tissue. It can be recognized

41
00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:32.680
as morphologically distinct from normal tissue, either macroscopically,

42
00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:36.260
as seen on the right-hand side for a cervical pre-cancer,

43
00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:40.320
or histologically, seen in the bottom right for a skin

44
00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:44.320
pre-cancer. Importantly, pre-cancers have a propensity to

45
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:45.609
progress to cancer,

46
00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:48.060
and it's important to

47
00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:52.220
identify them early, as there are some options to intervene,

48
00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:56.840
such as polypectomy as a surgical intervention or

49
00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.960
mammography or a CT scan for surveillance

50
00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:02.890
for less serious pre-cancers.

51
00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:09.130
I've used the term pre-cancer pretty definitively, but actually, it's

52
00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:13.000
become clear over the last decades that pre-cancer

53
00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:15.519
is a little bit more nebulous than you might believe.

54
00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:20.140
So screening programs over the last decade have found that pre-cancers are

55
00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:22.900
much more prevalent than they were previously thought to be,

56
00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:27.460
ranging from 10% to 50% of the

57
00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:30.040
population, depending on the tissue that we're looking at.

58
00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.020
However, the vast majority of pre-cancers will never progress to cancer,

59
00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:39.900
and the progression rate can vary from, as you see, less than 1% for

60
00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.780
pancreatic cysts all the way up to 25% for breast

61
00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:44.500
DCIS.

62
00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:48.800
Importantly, overdiagnosis is not risk-free.

63
00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:52.609
If you intervene, there are possibilities for surgical

64
00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:55.420
complications such as sepsis, and

65
00:03:56.580 --> 00:04:00.329
diagnosing a patient with a pre-cancer comes with some psychological stress as

66
00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:03.200
well, which can lead to adverse outcomes such as,

67
00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:06.040
in extreme cases, suicide.

68
00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:10.540
So the real question is, can we better stratify the 1% to 25% of

69
00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.820
pre-cancers that will progress from the 75% to

70
00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:17.780
99% that will never progress? And maybe we should think of them as something

71
00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:19.399
distinct from pre-cancer.

72
00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:25.200
To do this, we've put together a comprehensive data set of pre-cancers.

73
00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:29.440
Initially, we had just over 1,700 samples, but

74
00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:32.580
after rigorous quality control, this dropped down to just under

75
00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:36.440
1,500 pre-cancer samples from 33 different

76
00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:40.320
pre-cancer types spanning 24 different tissues in the human body.

77
00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:44.440
These were subject to a mixture of whole genome sequencing and whole exome

78
00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:48.120
sequencing, and run through a standardized NGS

79
00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:50.220
pipeline for mutation calling.

80
00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:55.120
We focused on somatic data types for this study, identifying

81
00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:58.600
mutations, some derived metrics such as

82
00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:02.640
ploidy, percent genome aberrant, and tumor mutational burden.

83
00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:06.920
We also did some driver calling, and we looked at mutational

84
00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.760
signatures such as SBS signatures and copy number signatures.

85
00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:17.280
The first thing that we can look at from this data is the genome-wide

86
00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:20.940
heterogeneity that we see in pre-cancer, and it's really

87
00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:24.920
quite extreme when you look at it. So this top panel here is

88
00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:28.740
the coding SBS and Indel burden across the coding

89
00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:32.620
genome. And this ranges from less than 10 coding

90
00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:36.600
mutations in the coding genome, as you can see on the left-hand side for

91
00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:40.660
testis pre-cancers, all the way up to over 3,000 coding

92
00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:44.620
mutations, which we see in a few colon adenomas and

93
00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:48.880
some skin pre-cancers. So this represents really a large level of

94
00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:51.580
inter-tissue heterogeneity at a mutational burden

95
00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:55.536
level.We also see heterogeneity at an intra

96
00:05:55.576 --> 00:05:59.536
precancer level. And I'm just showing here for colon adenomas,

97
00:06:00.256 --> 00:06:02.396
where we have the bulk of the tumors showing

98
00:06:03.476 --> 00:06:07.196
about 1.5-ish coding SBS and

99
00:06:07.276 --> 00:06:09.335
indel per megabase.

100
00:06:10.196 --> 00:06:13.726
But we do see some hypermutators, and we have verified that these have

101
00:06:13.736 --> 00:06:17.616
mutations in MLH1 or MSH2. I remind you, these

102
00:06:17.636 --> 00:06:21.556
are precancers and not cancers, and we see the hypermutator phenotype

103
00:06:21.596 --> 00:06:23.576
at this early stage of tumorigenesis.

104
00:06:25.316 --> 00:06:27.616
We also see intra-tissue heterogeneity.

105
00:06:28.016 --> 00:06:31.576
So both of these are colon precancers, and we can see that they

106
00:06:31.656 --> 00:06:35.076
vary in their average mutational burden across

107
00:06:35.136 --> 00:06:38.416
these different precancer types within the same tissue.

108
00:06:40.056 --> 00:06:43.916
We also see similar levels of heterogeneity in the copy number profiles

109
00:06:44.256 --> 00:06:47.756
as opposed to SBS and indel profiles I showed you previously.

110
00:06:48.096 --> 00:06:51.686
So here in the middle panel, we have the percent of genome aberrant to copy number

111
00:06:51.796 --> 00:06:55.566
alterations. And at the bottom, we have the percentage of samples that are whole

112
00:06:55.636 --> 00:06:59.176
genome doubled. And again, these range from precancers that have

113
00:06:59.216 --> 00:07:03.016
essentially nothing going on in terms of copy number, all the way up

114
00:07:03.096 --> 00:07:06.556
to precancers that have, on average, 70% of the

115
00:07:06.596 --> 00:07:10.536
genome altered by some kind of copy number alteration, and as

116
00:07:10.576 --> 00:07:13.516
many as 68% of samples being whole genome doubled.

117
00:07:14.496 --> 00:07:16.256
So again, a large level of heterogeneity.

118
00:07:18.116 --> 00:07:21.636
Next, we wanted to look into driver gene alterations.

119
00:07:22.836 --> 00:07:26.496
So, I can't go into all the detail, but this panel shows a

120
00:07:26.536 --> 00:07:30.316
number of bona fide cancer driver genes, and

121
00:07:30.356 --> 00:07:33.936
we see driver alterations in these genes at this early level of

122
00:07:33.976 --> 00:07:37.796
tumorigenesis as well. So the highlighted section here is showing

123
00:07:37.876 --> 00:07:41.016
APC alterations in colorectal

124
00:07:41.056 --> 00:07:44.936
precancers. We see them at this early stage, and we also

125
00:07:45.016 --> 00:07:48.876
see double hit mutations in, for instance, TP53

126
00:07:48.936 --> 00:07:52.295
and CDKN2A at this early stage of tumorigenesis.

127
00:07:53.736 --> 00:07:57.376
Importantly, 43% of the samples in our study showed no

128
00:07:57.416 --> 00:07:59.316
detectable driver gene alterations.

129
00:07:59.856 --> 00:08:03.135
Compare this to 11% in TCGA across cancers.

130
00:08:03.916 --> 00:08:07.636
So this really indicates that we need to look beyond driver gene alterations to

131
00:08:07.696 --> 00:08:10.456
understand what is going on in these lesions.

132
00:08:11.896 --> 00:08:15.556
To do this, I wanted to take a holistic approach across our data

133
00:08:15.636 --> 00:08:19.216
set. So I combined aneuploidy data, driver

134
00:08:19.296 --> 00:08:23.216
alterations, SBS signatures, copy number signatures, and

135
00:08:23.316 --> 00:08:26.716
our previously shown genome-wide metrics of genomic

136
00:08:26.756 --> 00:08:29.716
instability across our data set and across

137
00:08:29.756 --> 00:08:33.415
precancers. And I put these into a random forest model to try and

138
00:08:33.466 --> 00:08:36.736
predict whether a sample is precancer or cancer.

139
00:08:38.016 --> 00:08:40.937
Each of these vertical bars indicates an individual patient.

140
00:08:41.937 --> 00:08:45.686
And a value of 1.0 indicates that that sample was

141
00:08:45.696 --> 00:08:49.616
predicted to be 100% precancer-like, and a value of

142
00:08:49.856 --> 00:08:53.776
0.0 indicates the sample was predicted to be 100% cancer-like

143
00:08:54.196 --> 00:08:55.146
at a genomic level.

144
00:08:56.496 --> 00:09:00.126
So again, we see large heterogeneity here, and I'll just focus on

145
00:09:00.476 --> 00:09:03.096
one tissue to give you a through line.

146
00:09:03.476 --> 00:09:06.956
So if we look at lung precancers, there is a

147
00:09:06.996 --> 00:09:10.816
hypothesized progression from hyperplasia to adenocarcinoma in

148
00:09:10.836 --> 00:09:14.356
situ. And if we look at these two precancer types within

149
00:09:14.416 --> 00:09:17.796
this result, we see that the cancer-like

150
00:09:17.816 --> 00:09:21.626
score or one minus the precancer-like score increases

151
00:09:21.936 --> 00:09:25.836
as you move from hyperplasia to adenocarcinoma in situ, perhaps

152
00:09:25.876 --> 00:09:29.136
suggesting that genomic complexity is increasing as you

153
00:09:29.156 --> 00:09:32.236
progress through the different stages of precancer.

154
00:09:33.796 --> 00:09:37.196
We also have data from adenocarcinoma in situ.

155
00:09:37.276 --> 00:09:41.236
These are squamous cell lung precancers, and these dichotomize

156
00:09:41.276 --> 00:09:45.216
into two individual groups, one showing a high

157
00:09:45.296 --> 00:09:48.736
precancer-like genomic phenotype and one showing a high cancer-like

158
00:09:48.796 --> 00:09:52.596
phenotype, indicating that maybe these dichotomize into low-risk

159
00:09:52.676 --> 00:09:55.676
carcinoma in situ and high-risk carcinoma in situ.

160
00:09:56.486 --> 00:10:00.076
Unfortunately for this precancer type, we don't have the clinical

161
00:10:00.096 --> 00:10:03.716
data to really answer whether this is what we're seeing.

162
00:10:03.836 --> 00:10:07.336
However, for one of our data sets, we do have such

163
00:10:07.576 --> 00:10:11.556
information. For our Barrett's esophagus data, we have cancer outcome data

164
00:10:11.635 --> 00:10:15.596
for these patients, and we can see that this same score correlates

165
00:10:15.636 --> 00:10:19.606
with cancer outcomes. So as you move from the left to the right, we move from

166
00:10:19.656 --> 00:10:23.436
no cancer outcome patients to cancer outcome patients, where the

167
00:10:23.496 --> 00:10:26.576
sample was taken asynchronously to the cancer.

168
00:10:26.716 --> 00:10:28.676
So the sample was taken previous to cancer.

169
00:10:29.356 --> 00:10:32.896
And on the right-hand side, the sample was taken synchronously with the cancer.

170
00:10:34.026 --> 00:10:37.886
And we can see that the cancer-like score increases as we move through those

171
00:10:37.956 --> 00:10:41.036
different stages, suggesting that this score has some

172
00:10:41.096 --> 00:10:43.836
utility in finding

173
00:10:45.316 --> 00:10:46.616
less benign precancers.

174
00:10:48.706 --> 00:10:52.576
We can then ask what features predict malignant potential using this model.

175
00:10:52.916 --> 00:10:56.576
And I've just focused on the top 40 features here, and the top

176
00:10:56.676 --> 00:11:00.476
three features were the same features I showed you in the first results

177
00:11:00.496 --> 00:11:02.536
slide. Tumor mutational burden,

178
00:11:03.606 --> 00:11:07.516
ploidy, and the proportion of genome aberrant by copy number alterations

179
00:11:07.536 --> 00:11:11.376
were the three most important features for determining malignant potential.

180
00:11:13.276 --> 00:11:17.156
We also see copy number alterations across a large number of our

181
00:11:17.176 --> 00:11:21.036
top 40 features. These seem to be key in determining

182
00:11:21.056 --> 00:11:24.576
whether something has malignant potential or not.

183
00:11:25.416 --> 00:11:28.976
We also see a couple of driver gene alterations, CDKN2A and TP53.

184
00:11:29.396 --> 00:11:32.816
Again, the two most commonly altered genes in cancer and in

185
00:11:32.856 --> 00:11:33.476
precancer,

186
00:11:34.456 --> 00:11:38.176
and also a couple of signatures of hypermutation.

187
00:11:41.376 --> 00:11:45.316
So in summary, we've shown a proof of concept that genomic profiling can

188
00:11:45.336 --> 00:11:49.126
discern precancers from cancers and that genomic variability

189
00:11:49.256 --> 00:11:51.776
acts as the soil within which malignancy develops.

190
00:11:52.776 --> 00:11:53.536
We would love to

191
00:11:54.736 --> 00:11:58.696
extend this to really ask the question that we want, which is: can we

192
00:11:58.736 --> 00:12:02.016
separate indolent precancers from high-risk

193
00:12:02.076 --> 00:12:05.916
precancers? But we need better clinical data to be able to answer that

194
00:12:05.956 --> 00:12:06.836
specific question.

195
00:12:07.796 --> 00:12:11.136
There are some data modalities that were not included in this study that might be

196
00:12:11.176 --> 00:12:15.126
important in explaining what is causing some of these lesions, and

197
00:12:15.156 --> 00:12:19.036
those might include epigenetic factors, transcriptomic factors, the immune

198
00:12:19.056 --> 00:12:21.996
environment, germline features, and structural

199
00:12:22.076 --> 00:12:26.006
variants.I would just like to thank everybody in the lab and all the

200
00:12:26.026 --> 00:12:28.686
collaborators who've worked on this. In particular, Phoebe He.

201
00:12:29.606 --> 00:12:33.086
She did a huge amount of work on this study, so thanks to her.

202
00:12:34.106 --> 00:12:36.876
And if you have any questions, I'd be happy to answer them now.

203
00:12:53.096 --> 00:12:55.546
I think everybody can hear me? Ah, okay.

204
00:12:57.996 --> 00:12:58.606
Any question?

205
00:12:59.946 --> 00:13:01.246
Can I... Okay.

206
00:13:03.246 --> 00:13:04.956
Can I start with the question?

207
00:13:05.386 --> 00:13:05.456
Sure.

208
00:13:07.386 --> 00:13:11.046
So the data that you have shown are very interesting, but

209
00:13:11.386 --> 00:13:15.266
I have the impression that we have this continuum of data for the

210
00:13:15.286 --> 00:13:19.086
patients that finally develop a cancer, but we are missing data

211
00:13:19.186 --> 00:13:22.866
for the patients or non-patients in reality

212
00:13:23.626 --> 00:13:23.766
for

213
00:13:24.646 --> 00:13:27.705
whom this indolent disease remain like this.

214
00:13:28.116 --> 00:13:28.345
Yes.

215
00:13:29.086 --> 00:13:31.786
How do you think we can fill in this gap?

216
00:13:32.286 --> 00:13:35.726
There are some ideas, some effort that are

217
00:13:35.946 --> 00:13:36.886
currently ongoing.

218
00:13:37.946 --> 00:13:41.926
I'm not aware of any efforts that are currently ongoing, but I think it needs to

219
00:13:41.966 --> 00:13:43.626
be in discussion with clinicians.

220
00:13:44.426 --> 00:13:48.406
At the moment, part of the problem is that some pre-cancers will regress,

221
00:13:48.476 --> 00:13:49.446
so they kind of disappear.

222
00:13:50.506 --> 00:13:53.806
And then once they've regressed, patients stop going to the doctor for them.

223
00:13:53.846 --> 00:13:56.126
They're not interested in them anymore, which makes sense.

224
00:13:56.926 --> 00:14:00.826
But I think maybe it would be beneficial if clinicians

225
00:14:00.886 --> 00:14:04.526
had these in the back of their mind and could follow up these patients if

226
00:14:04.566 --> 00:14:08.086
possible. It's really a data collection problem.

227
00:14:11.746 --> 00:14:12.786
Hi. Great talk.

228
00:14:13.186 --> 00:14:13.686
Thank you.

229
00:14:13.746 --> 00:14:17.276
I'm wondering, do you guys have any pre-cancer lesions from any

230
00:14:18.006 --> 00:14:21.346
patients with germline predisposition syndromes?

231
00:14:21.926 --> 00:14:22.726
In those cases,

232
00:14:23.746 --> 00:14:26.086
do you see those corresponding signatures?

233
00:14:26.566 --> 00:14:29.466
Or I guess, in other words, are these genes haploinsufficient?

234
00:14:29.946 --> 00:14:33.725
Mm-hmm. That's a good question. We wanted to exclude germline

235
00:14:34.206 --> 00:14:37.986
predispositions in this study. But it is something that is worth looking

236
00:14:38.006 --> 00:14:38.366
into.

237
00:14:43.966 --> 00:14:44.846
All right. Thank you.

238
00:14:44.886 --> 00:14:45.015
Thank you.

239
00:14:45.015 --> 00:14:46.646
Thank you.

