So my lab's really interested in understanding, basically in breast cancer,

249
00:15:28.266 --> 00:15:30.766
why these respond very poorly to immune checkpoint blockade.

250
00:15:30.806 --> 00:15:34.186
So what are the immunosuppressive factors driving these poor responses?

251
00:15:34.686 --> 00:15:38.106
Particularly in the triple negative breast cancer subset, where we know a large

252
00:15:38.166 --> 00:15:39.826
majority of these are essentially immune positive.

253
00:15:39.866 --> 00:15:42.926
They have a nice and rich score for immune infiltration,

254
00:15:43.766 --> 00:15:46.346
which presumably should mark a highly responsive population.

255
00:15:47.306 --> 00:15:51.086
And we were very interested when this paper came out from UCSF, which noted that

256
00:15:51.096 --> 00:15:54.746
this immune infiltration is very related to this DNA repair defect

257
00:15:54.786 --> 00:15:58.486
signature, they noted in this fairly large cohort of patients from the

258
00:15:58.546 --> 00:15:59.466
I-SPY 2 trial.

259
00:16:00.786 --> 00:16:03.946
And so why might this be the case? And it's been really nicely shown by multiple

260
00:16:04.006 --> 00:16:04.846
groups that

261
00:16:05.686 --> 00:16:08.986
when you have defects in DNA repair, and these are mostly related to BRCA1

262
00:16:09.006 --> 00:16:12.766
deficiencies, you wind up having the accumulation of damaged

263
00:16:12.786 --> 00:16:16.706
DNA in the cytosol of tumor cells. This then leads

264
00:16:16.746 --> 00:16:20.486
to activation of the cGAS and STING pathway, with the

265
00:16:20.526 --> 00:16:23.876
intermediate production of this dinucleotides called cGAMP, which we'll touch on a

266
00:16:23.906 --> 00:16:27.306
little bit later. That then turns on a classic type I interferon response,

267
00:16:27.926 --> 00:16:31.246
and then essentially has that classic immune activation.

268
00:16:32.246 --> 00:16:35.726
Notably, several groups, particularly the Rolle and the Li lab from Stanford,

269
00:16:35.866 --> 00:16:39.506
showed that not only does this pathway turn activate in tumor cells,

270
00:16:40.306 --> 00:16:43.545
but the release of this cGAMP intermediate can actually happen into extracellular

271
00:16:43.606 --> 00:16:46.886
space, and they can activate the host immune response as well.

272
00:16:47.306 --> 00:16:50.886
So essentially when you have this DNA repair defect, you can turn on both

273
00:16:51.186 --> 00:16:53.066
tumor and host immune activation.

274
00:16:54.466 --> 00:16:55.706
So then this should be a really good thing.

275
00:16:55.746 --> 00:16:58.546
We should see really high immune infiltration, and so why don't these patients

276
00:16:58.626 --> 00:16:59.106
respond?

277
00:16:59.966 --> 00:17:03.546
Well, one thing was identified both by the Li lab originally, as well as some extra

278
00:17:03.566 --> 00:17:05.926
work by the Backhome lab, where they showed that there's this

279
00:17:06.946 --> 00:17:09.206
ectonucleotidase called ENPP1 on the surface.

280
00:17:09.366 --> 00:17:12.666
This is in the same family as the CD39 and CD73 family.

281
00:17:13.166 --> 00:17:16.727
And what this does is actually cleave this dinucleotide into its

282
00:17:16.946 --> 00:17:19.126
requisite components, AMP and GMP,

283
00:17:20.106 --> 00:17:22.866
as well as degrade extracellular ATP.

284
00:17:22.886 --> 00:17:26.386
And this can then produce, through the CD73 pathway, suppressive

285
00:17:26.446 --> 00:17:28.086
adenosine and essentially shut down.

286
00:17:28.786 --> 00:17:32.326
So as Tom Gaisky say, you're essentially turning off the gas as well as applying

287
00:17:32.346 --> 00:17:33.406
the brakes at the same time.

288
00:17:34.686 --> 00:17:38.366
But despite this, if you knock out this gene from tumor cells, at least the

289
00:17:38.386 --> 00:17:42.106
primary tumor, it doesn't care. There is less metastasis, and they do become

290
00:17:42.166 --> 00:17:45.826
slightly more susceptible to immune checkpoint blockade, but primary tumors grow as

291
00:17:45.886 --> 00:17:48.046
if nothing had happened. And so we're really curious.

292
00:17:48.086 --> 00:17:51.026
Well, maybe the problem is not that this is not an interesting molecule.

293
00:17:51.066 --> 00:17:53.426
Maybe the problem is we're just asking the wrong question in the wrong model

294
00:17:53.486 --> 00:17:53.906
system.

295
00:17:54.866 --> 00:17:58.486
And so my student in the lab went to the human

296
00:17:58.626 --> 00:18:02.506
TCA datasets and asked, "Where is ENPP1 important?" And so

297
00:18:02.786 --> 00:18:06.626
if you look at BRCA1 type disease, you see expression of ENPP1, it doesn't matter

298
00:18:06.666 --> 00:18:10.226
in terms of outcome. And in this very small group of patients,

299
00:18:10.846 --> 00:18:14.126
you see with those who have BRCA mutations, you see a large difference in the

300
00:18:14.146 --> 00:18:18.126
survival of these patients. Now, this is probably heavily biased by subtype and a

301
00:18:18.146 --> 00:18:18.506
really low

302
00:18:19.326 --> 00:18:23.270
number of patients, and so she also scanned another datasetThat came

303
00:18:23.310 --> 00:18:26.370
out here in 2019. And this is all TNBC patients.

304
00:18:26.810 --> 00:18:30.690
And again, you see patients who have functional BRCA1 genes, both in

305
00:18:30.710 --> 00:18:34.070
terms of lack of mutations as well as a high expression,

306
00:18:34.850 --> 00:18:38.600
have essentially no survival advantage or disadvantage with high expression,

307
00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:42.650
whereas those with a non-functional mutation do see the survival difference.

308
00:18:43.550 --> 00:18:46.790
So with that, we essentially went to our mouse models.

309
00:18:46.830 --> 00:18:50.590
We made a BRCA deficient mouse model to interrogate this in

310
00:18:50.610 --> 00:18:54.110
syngeneic model systems, and we made two cell lines with BRCA deficiency.

311
00:18:54.410 --> 00:18:57.930
Both of these had very high prevalence of the cytosolic double-strand DNA that we

312
00:18:57.950 --> 00:19:01.760
expected, shown here in green. Notably, they also very highly

313
00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:05.710
expressed the essentially induced expression of this ENPP1

314
00:19:06.170 --> 00:19:06.830
nucleotide.

315
00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:09.610
And so we want to interrogate what role this had.

316
00:19:09.970 --> 00:19:13.150
So when we knocked it out of other tumor models, shown here is the PYMT

317
00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:17.270
E0771, as well as something else we made called the KP1 TNBC

318
00:19:17.290 --> 00:19:19.130
cell line, essentially no difference.

319
00:19:19.310 --> 00:19:20.990
Repeating what had been published in the literature.

320
00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:24.810
But now when we put it into BRCA deficient lines, now we saw very substantial

321
00:19:24.820 --> 00:19:28.770
differences in tumor growth in the absence of any kind of therapeutic intervention.

322
00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:31.990
If we had a slightly slower growing model, it was to the point that not only did we

323
00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:35.770
have slower tumors growing, but we actually had rejection in about half of the mice

324
00:19:35.970 --> 00:19:37.670
that had implanted with this tumor model.

325
00:19:39.110 --> 00:19:42.630
And so what was going on here? Maybe not surprising for having tumor rejection, we

326
00:19:42.650 --> 00:19:44.390
had higher infiltration of CD8 T cells.

327
00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:48.010
These CD8 T cells were more interferon gamma and expressing,

328
00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:51.830
as well as slightly higher infiltration of other things like CD4s and NK cells.

329
00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:56.050
Notably, if we depleted CD8 T cells, the phenotype completely disappeared, whereas

330
00:19:56.070 --> 00:19:59.790
if we depleted CD8s and NK cells, the phenotype was fairly modest.

331
00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:04.030
So we did single cell to understand what was happening to all these immune cells

332
00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:07.870
here in the deficient tumors. What we saw most prominently was large

333
00:20:07.910 --> 00:20:09.830
changes in macrophage gene expression profiles,

334
00:20:10.730 --> 00:20:13.810
and in particularly expression of genes related to class one and class two

335
00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:18.540
expression. We confirmed these by flow cytometry, releasing a higher

336
00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:22.250
expression of antigen presentation by these macrophages present within the

337
00:20:22.490 --> 00:20:23.870
tumors deficient in ENPP1.

338
00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:28.330
We then went to ask, does these macrophages actually responding to this

339
00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:30.010
extracellular cGAMP production?

340
00:20:30.610 --> 00:20:34.430
So we took advantage of these STING flox mice, and if we look at

341
00:20:34.450 --> 00:20:38.370
control mice, the tumors grow slower when they lack ENPP1.

342
00:20:38.410 --> 00:20:41.520
If we put them in mice which have a LysM-Cre where they lose expression of this

343
00:20:41.590 --> 00:20:44.790
STING gene in macrophages, these no longer have a difference in growth.

344
00:20:45.410 --> 00:20:49.130
And as a control, we also put these in mice that lack STING expression in dendritic

345
00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:52.610
cells, because classically it's thought that STING activation in dendritic cells is

346
00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:53.930
really driving anti-tumor immunity.

347
00:20:54.330 --> 00:20:57.410
But we found this was irrelevant, at least in this one model system.

348
00:20:58.470 --> 00:21:02.270
This change in tumor volume was marked by similar matches in essentially a loss of

349
00:21:02.290 --> 00:21:06.230
the CD8 T cell infiltration, shown here in the middle, loss of CD4, CD8s,

350
00:21:06.550 --> 00:21:10.390
no longer an increase in interferon gamma expression, and no longer a change

351
00:21:10.430 --> 00:21:13.310
in the phenotype of macrophages that we had been seeing.

352
00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:18.050
We also confirmed that this was functionally relevant, so not just changes in the

353
00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:22.040
genome or the protein level. We actually took macrophages out from tumors, and

354
00:21:22.250 --> 00:21:25.010
shown here is a classic T cell suppression assay.

355
00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:27.810
So shown here, if you activate T cells, they proliferate very nicely.

356
00:21:28.330 --> 00:21:31.770
If you incubate them with macrophages from tumors, essentially shuts down the

357
00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:34.930
proliferation. But if you take them from macrophages from tumors that

358
00:21:35.870 --> 00:21:39.310
do not express ENPP1, they now proliferate as happily as if they'd not been seeing

359
00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:42.410
macrophages at all, at least at this lower concentration of

360
00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:46.790
macrophages. And notably, when we did the same thing with STING flox mice, this

361
00:21:46.830 --> 00:21:50.110
phenotype went away. So STING activation in macrophages was actually required for

362
00:21:50.150 --> 00:21:52.850
this version of the immunosuppressive phenotype.

363
00:21:54.290 --> 00:21:54.560
Now,

364
00:21:55.590 --> 00:21:59.110
we'd assumed that production of

365
00:21:59.150 --> 00:22:02.980
cGAS and STING and cGAMP would be from tumor cells, but we wanted to confirm that

366
00:22:03.010 --> 00:22:06.180
was the case. And so what we did was we knocked out the cGAS gene from tumor cells,

367
00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:09.780
assuming that that would then prevent any kind of signature that we were seeing.

368
00:22:10.330 --> 00:22:12.670
And indeed, when we knocked out cGAS, the tumors grew normally.

369
00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:16.050
So if there's no cGAMP in the tumors, there's no activation of the immune response.

370
00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:19.550
Now, as a control, we also knocked out STING from tumor cells, thinking that this

371
00:22:19.570 --> 00:22:23.490
would have no real phenotype, because presumably the degradation of the

372
00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:26.030
extracellular molecule would activate the host and not the tumor.

373
00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:28.510
But in fact, we found that it was identical.

374
00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:32.850
So the host and the tumor response to STING was equally critical for

375
00:22:32.890 --> 00:22:36.850
this role of this one extracellular nucleotide, suggesting that the

376
00:22:36.870 --> 00:22:40.480
release of this molecule by tumor cells is actually, in an autocrine or

377
00:22:40.629 --> 00:22:43.250
paracrine fashion, activating neighboring tumor cells.

378
00:22:44.890 --> 00:22:48.810
To ask what was happening here, we did bulk RNA-seq, and we found

379
00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:52.820
that, essentially in the absence of ENPP1, and the phenotype was reversed by

380
00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:56.630
the lack of tumor STING, we had higher expression of all the classic

381
00:22:56.830 --> 00:23:00.170
immune markers, but particularly a higher expression of MHC class I on the tumor

382
00:23:00.230 --> 00:23:04.150
cells. And then inversely, we saw a very low expression and low infiltration

383
00:23:04.210 --> 00:23:07.530
of neutrophils, which a point I won't touch on at all later on

384
00:23:07.570 --> 00:23:10.820
today. We confirmed the increased expression of MHC-I

385
00:23:11.630 --> 00:23:14.390
on the tumor cells, as shown here by flow cytometry.

386
00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:18.770
This also led to increased expression of a model tumor antigen, which we put

387
00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:21.110
inside the tumor cells, in this case Siglec-F.

388
00:23:22.770 --> 00:23:26.330
And then these tumor cells were now more susceptible to direct CD8 mediated killing

389
00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:29.650
in an antigen-specific manner. And finally, we actually tried to put these back

390
00:23:29.670 --> 00:23:33.550
into mice to really characterize what these tumors were looking at, if we

391
00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:36.950
had no higher antigen expression, we could track the immune response.

392
00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:39.110
But what we found was when they were expressing OVA, they just couldn't grow.

393
00:23:39.470 --> 00:23:42.490
So if we just a little bit increased the antigenicity of these tumors in the

394
00:23:42.530 --> 00:23:45.710
absence of EP1, they were completely unable to grow in these mice any longer.

395
00:23:47.270 --> 00:23:48.730
So moving beyond just a single

396
00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:54.110
agent or a direct single knockout, we

397
00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:57.490
interrogated the response of these tumors to standard of care of

398
00:23:57.930 --> 00:23:59.290
essentially, well, in this case,

399
00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:02.970
niraparib, which is not standard of care for breast cancer, but it was a really

400
00:24:02.990 --> 00:24:03.450
effective

401
00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:08.500
PARP inhibitor in our hands. And then we also interrogated

402
00:24:08.550 --> 00:24:12.030
response to anti-PD-1. Notably, as in clinical trials, if you combine

403
00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:14.910
niraparib and anti-PD-1 in patients, there's no effect.

404
00:24:15.210 --> 00:24:18.870
So the combination, although it was a good idea, we don't see any effect in the

405
00:24:18.910 --> 00:24:21.110
patients over multiple clinical trials.

406
00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:24.700
But notably, when we did the same thing in the ENPP1 knockouts, each alone had a

407
00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:28.220
similar effect, but when we combined them, we now started seeing really prolonged

408
00:24:28.270 --> 00:24:31.950
tumor control, and the occasional rejection as well, which then led to

409
00:24:31.990 --> 00:24:34.210
enhanced survival only in this group.

410
00:24:34.410 --> 00:24:38.334
So we only saw combination efficacy in this one group.So

411
00:24:38.494 --> 00:24:40.734
knowing that if we knock it out, it's important.

412
00:24:40.794 --> 00:24:42.974
We also want to ask, can we target this therapeutically?

413
00:24:43.834 --> 00:24:47.454
So a chemist at Moffitt, as well as a

414
00:24:47.534 --> 00:24:51.114
protein engineer at Moffitt got together and developed

415
00:24:51.874 --> 00:24:55.514
or remade the inhibitors that had been published by the Lee and Wells lab at

416
00:24:55.654 --> 00:24:59.514
Stanford and UCSF respectively. And both of these work fairly well at actually

417
00:24:59.534 --> 00:25:02.914
inhibiting tumor growth in our model system, achieving roughly half the tumor

418
00:25:02.954 --> 00:25:05.614
control we see when we knock out the gene entirely.

419
00:25:05.954 --> 00:25:08.574
But this wasn't quite where we wanted, so we tried to make our own antibody as

420
00:25:08.634 --> 00:25:11.734
well. We found this antibody that was made by the Lucca lab.

421
00:25:12.434 --> 00:25:15.674
It's actually an antibody and then put into either a human or mouse

422
00:25:16.414 --> 00:25:20.074
construct. We found this was quite efficient at binding. It was very stable.

423
00:25:20.874 --> 00:25:24.274
And then it worked on both human and mouse to bind very well to the different cell

424
00:25:24.314 --> 00:25:27.434
lines, as well as to inhibit the degradation of CCAMP.

425
00:25:29.214 --> 00:25:32.394
And importantly, when we put this back in the mouse, we found that this B7 antibody

426
00:25:32.454 --> 00:25:36.394
that targets very effectively human and mouse CMPP1, was equal to the

427
00:25:36.414 --> 00:25:39.034
knocking out the gene entirely in tumors at controlling tumor volume.

428
00:25:39.574 --> 00:25:43.344
And then both as a single agent and in combination with niraparib and anti-PD1,

429
00:25:43.914 --> 00:25:46.754
we had really prolonged tumor control in these mice.

430
00:25:48.294 --> 00:25:51.214
So with that, I think I've run out of time, so I'll skip the summary slide.

431
00:25:51.514 --> 00:25:54.874
But what I really wanted to do is thank the really talented work from my lab,

432
00:25:54.954 --> 00:25:57.844
particularly Jiayi Li, who led this project from the start,

433
00:25:58.874 --> 00:26:01.794
as well as help from the Lucca lab and Charlotte.

434
00:26:01.974 --> 00:26:02.554
I mean, his lab,

435
00:26:03.374 --> 00:26:06.994
various other collaborators at Moffitt, including the Lopucki lab, and then the

436
00:26:07.034 --> 00:26:09.774
funding shown here. With that, I'll take any questions. Thank you.

437
00:26:12.054 --> 00:26:22.914
Any

438
00:26:22.974 --> 00:26:24.134
question?

439
00:26:26.994 --> 00:26:28.014
It was all clear, so that's good.

440
00:26:30.194 --> 00:26:33.734
Can I ask, how do you imagine a clinical trial

441
00:26:34.514 --> 00:26:36.634
with the PARP inhibitor and an antibody?

442
00:26:38.174 --> 00:26:40.894
I would hope that it may work.

443
00:26:42.574 --> 00:26:46.464
Perhaps in refractory patients, we could try the antibody as a single

444
00:26:46.514 --> 00:26:49.054
agent. Ideally, probably in combination, though.

445
00:26:49.794 --> 00:26:52.954
When it's most effective would be obviously the earlier we go, the more effective

446
00:26:52.994 --> 00:26:56.254
it might be. But if we can repeat those early trials with the inhibitor,

447
00:26:57.114 --> 00:26:58.614
and with standard of care, that would be ideal.

448
00:27:01.594 --> 00:27:01.974
Thank you.

449
00:27:02.134 --> 00:27:03.814
Thank you.

450
00:27:07.314 --> 00:27:09.234
Dr. Ahat will join us.

451
00:27:12.394 --> 00:27:15.914
And his talk is titled Mechanisms of Tumor Dormancy Through Immune Niche

452
00:27:16.014 --> 00:27:19.174
Formation and Its Impact on Immune Therapeutic Relapse.

453
00:27:20.654 --> 00:27:20.794
Yeah.

454
00:27:22.214 --> 00:27:25.734
Good evening, everyone. Thank you to the chair and ACR for the opportunity

455
00:27:27.094 --> 00:27:30.754
to present our work, which is about how some cancer

456
00:27:30.794 --> 00:27:34.714
cells survive the immune pressure by entering the tumor dormancy.

457
00:27:35.234 --> 00:27:38.654
And we just see the previous, our colleague showed the wonderful data in the breast

458
00:27:38.734 --> 00:27:42.724
cancer that anti-tumor immunity is so important, but not always. There is a caveat.

459
00:27:42.994 --> 00:27:45.444
That's what I'm going to talk about.

460
00:27:46.534 --> 00:27:48.674
So I don't have any financial things to disclose.

461
00:27:49.354 --> 00:27:52.804
This is my outline, where I will briefly set up the background,

462
00:27:52.974 --> 00:27:55.934
introduction of tumor dormancy, and our lab research.

463
00:27:56.514 --> 00:27:58.454
And I'll focus mainly on three questions.

464
00:27:58.634 --> 00:28:02.414
First, how tumor cells acquire the dormancy phenotype in our mouse

465
00:28:02.474 --> 00:28:03.614
model. The second,

466
00:28:04.794 --> 00:28:08.374
how they avoid immune elimination once dormant by

467
00:28:08.394 --> 00:28:09.794
acquiring distinct immune niche.

468
00:28:10.554 --> 00:28:13.594
And the third, I'll end with how their inhibitory access

469
00:28:14.514 --> 00:28:16.114
may provide a way to target relapse.

470
00:28:17.914 --> 00:28:18.054
So

471
00:28:19.674 --> 00:28:23.054
disseminated tumor cells from the primary tumor, they hide in

472
00:28:23.094 --> 00:28:26.654
non-dividing, a very slow-growing state called dormant state,

473
00:28:27.094 --> 00:28:30.774
which can give rise to the metastatic relapse months, years, even

474
00:28:30.874 --> 00:28:31.414
decades later.

475
00:28:32.254 --> 00:28:34.474
There are two main models established in the field.

476
00:28:34.774 --> 00:28:37.674
First is cellular dormancy, where cancer

477
00:28:38.514 --> 00:28:39.094
tumor cells

478
00:28:40.154 --> 00:28:44.084
enter reversible quiescent state by reducing the growth pathways and

479
00:28:44.134 --> 00:28:47.854
increase p38. There's another model where there is tumor mass dormancy,

480
00:28:48.134 --> 00:28:50.414
where proliferation versus

481
00:28:51.734 --> 00:28:54.714
