1309
01:17:34.416 --> 01:17:37.256
So next abstract will be presented by Dr.

1310
01:17:37.576 --> 01:17:41.336
Tan, Active RAS inhibition intercepts pancreas cancer in

1311
01:17:41.396 --> 01:17:42.316
mice. Thank you.

1312
01:17:43.816 --> 01:17:45.216
Hey. Oh, loud.

1313
01:17:46.616 --> 01:17:48.636
Thank you for the opportunity to present.

1314
01:17:48.856 --> 01:17:52.756
Today, I will be showing some preclinical work

1315
01:17:52.796 --> 01:17:55.605
that supports a strategy for pancreas cancer interception.

1316
01:17:56.716 --> 01:17:57.786
Here are my disclosures.

1317
01:17:59.336 --> 01:18:02.256
And as you guys may have heard, RAS is drugable.

1318
01:18:02.336 --> 01:18:05.836
And the molecular glues by Revolution Medicines can allow

1319
01:18:05.876 --> 01:18:09.256
for these inhibitors to be both multi-selective

1320
01:18:09.816 --> 01:18:13.756
or mutant selective. And so RMC-7977

1321
01:18:13.816 --> 01:18:17.256
is the preclinical analog of diraxantrasib, which is a

1322
01:18:17.316 --> 01:18:20.496
multi-selective RAS inhibitor. And RMC-9945

1323
01:18:20.756 --> 01:18:24.516
is the preclinical analog of zoldanrasib, which is a

1324
01:18:24.576 --> 01:18:26.676
covalent G12D selective inhibitor.

1325
01:18:27.596 --> 01:18:31.436
And excitingly, what we've seen is that when we deploy these molecules

1326
01:18:31.476 --> 01:18:34.636
in metastatic pancreas cancer in the metastatic setting,

1327
01:18:35.436 --> 01:18:38.936
we see that the overall response rates and disease control rates

1328
01:18:39.016 --> 01:18:40.836
are profound.

1329
01:18:41.676 --> 01:18:45.336
And that this is actually changing the landscape and really presenting a

1330
01:18:45.406 --> 01:18:47.456
promising therapy for patients with PDAC.

1331
01:18:48.216 --> 01:18:49.616
However, despite

1332
01:18:50.576 --> 01:18:54.476
greater than 90% of PDAC having mutations in KRAS, we know

1333
01:18:54.516 --> 01:18:58.076
that RAS inhibition alone is going to be insufficient to cure this disease.

1334
01:18:59.216 --> 01:19:03.196
And that's not surprising because we know that tumor heterogeneity and

1335
01:19:03.216 --> 01:19:07.116
cellular plasticity are persistent issues when

1336
01:19:07.156 --> 01:19:08.956
we deal with single agent interventions.

1337
01:19:09.956 --> 01:19:13.816
And when we think about it, when we think about a normal cell becoming invasive

1338
01:19:13.876 --> 01:19:14.316
disease,

1339
01:19:15.176 --> 01:19:17.736
we know that its genetic diversity amplifies.

1340
01:19:19.336 --> 01:19:22.836
And yet despite that, at the point of peak genetic

1341
01:19:22.896 --> 01:19:26.716
diversity, AKA metastatic disease, is where we're

1342
01:19:26.816 --> 01:19:28.896
grossly deploying RAS inhibition.

1343
01:19:30.176 --> 01:19:33.696
However, we know that cancer is a Darwinian process, and so with all this

1344
01:19:33.776 --> 01:19:37.696
variation, it shouldn't be a surprise to know that there's going to be a cell

1345
01:19:37.716 --> 01:19:41.660
that survives a therapeutic insult.And so

1346
01:19:41.820 --> 01:19:45.780
unfortunately, this is always going to be an obstacle with our current paradigms

1347
01:19:45.820 --> 01:19:46.959
of cancer treatment.

1348
01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:51.560
And so I present to you an idea, cancer interception, which

1349
01:19:51.720 --> 01:19:55.480
tries to intervene earlier in those steps of tumorigenesis.

1350
01:20:01.100 --> 01:20:04.520
And with cancer interception, the thought is that we can intervene on these

1351
01:20:04.600 --> 01:20:07.940
precursor cells to impair their ability to become

1352
01:20:08.160 --> 01:20:08.660
cancer.

1353
01:20:10.180 --> 01:20:13.960
And ultimately, this can avoid all the heterogeneity and

1354
01:20:14.100 --> 01:20:17.500
the plasticity that may be seen in later stages of the disease.

1355
01:20:18.240 --> 01:20:21.780
And so when we look at this through the lens of pancreas cancer, we know that these

1356
01:20:21.840 --> 01:20:23.320
pre-early lesions,

1357
01:20:24.560 --> 01:20:27.980
we know that the acinar cells can undergo reversible metaplasia,

1358
01:20:28.620 --> 01:20:31.000
resulting in early lesions known as ADMs.

1359
01:20:31.800 --> 01:20:35.780
This process is typically reversible unless an acquisition of KRAS

1360
01:20:36.120 --> 01:20:37.360
occurs within these cells.

1361
01:20:38.300 --> 01:20:42.220
At this point, this becomes irreversible and panin lesions then result

1362
01:20:42.280 --> 01:20:46.260
within the pancreas. And then subsequent loss of tumor suppressor cells then

1363
01:20:46.320 --> 01:20:49.920
accelerates the path down tumorigenesis, and they become

1364
01:20:49.960 --> 01:20:53.640
invasive disease. And over the past couple of years, there's been a lot of

1365
01:20:53.680 --> 01:20:55.700
interesting research regarding panin.

1366
01:20:56.740 --> 01:20:57.920
First, we know that panin

1367
01:20:59.020 --> 01:21:01.620
are present in the majority of healthy people.

1368
01:21:02.810 --> 01:21:06.550
We also know that individuals can harbor hundreds of independent panin lesions,

1369
01:21:08.060 --> 01:21:10.640
and KRAS is ubiquitous within these lesions.

1370
01:21:11.320 --> 01:21:12.460
And so given this paradigm,

1371
01:21:13.300 --> 01:21:16.720
it's an interesting question, if these precursor lesions have RAS

1372
01:21:16.760 --> 01:21:17.420
mutations,

1373
01:21:18.240 --> 01:21:20.400
how long do we need to wait before we intervene on them?

1374
01:21:22.420 --> 01:21:25.220
And so we asked, do panin respond to RAS inhibition?

1375
01:21:26.720 --> 01:21:30.260
And in order to do this, we assessed this in the KPC mouse, which harbor both KRAS

1376
01:21:30.360 --> 01:21:34.280
G12D as well as a P53 mutation within the pancreas of

1377
01:21:34.300 --> 01:21:34.760
these mice.

1378
01:21:35.620 --> 01:21:39.600
On average, these mice develop panin by one to two months of age, develop

1379
01:21:39.680 --> 01:21:43.600
tumors by three to four months of age, and then they usually expire by five

1380
01:21:43.660 --> 01:21:44.220
months of age.

1381
01:21:45.020 --> 01:21:48.960
And so for this first experiment, we took nine-week-old KPC mice, which harbor

1382
01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:52.860
known panin lesions, and then exposed them to 10 days of

1383
01:21:52.900 --> 01:21:56.820
RAS inhibition. And then we evaluated them at endpoint using a

1384
01:21:56.860 --> 01:21:57.860
technique known as CODA.

1385
01:21:58.760 --> 01:22:02.280
For those of you guys that don't know, CODA is a technique that uses machine

1386
01:22:02.340 --> 01:22:05.820
learning to analyze serial sections of H&amp;Es,

1387
01:22:06.400 --> 01:22:10.060
and this allows for the 3D reconstruction of tissues.

1388
01:22:10.640 --> 01:22:13.940
In this case, when we apply it to the mouse pancreas, we can actually evaluate the

1389
01:22:13.960 --> 01:22:15.179
entirety of the mouse pancreas.

1390
01:22:16.020 --> 01:22:19.140
And then when we use CODA to identify

1391
01:22:19.620 --> 01:22:23.580
histologic lesions of interest, we can actually look

1392
01:22:23.600 --> 01:22:26.980
through the entire pancreas for these microscopic precursor lesions across our

1393
01:22:27.020 --> 01:22:28.100
experimental conditions.

1394
01:22:30.680 --> 01:22:34.640
And in this setting, when we reconstruct the pancreata under

1395
01:22:34.680 --> 01:22:38.360
these various conditions, we can see that RAS inhibition is eliminating these

1396
01:22:38.420 --> 01:22:42.360
precursor cells. Interestingly, even at this stage of the disease, if you

1397
01:22:42.480 --> 01:22:46.370
count the number of panin, it's about 400 at this

1398
01:22:46.420 --> 01:22:50.280
time point, and this significantly decreases as you expose these mice to RAS

1399
01:22:50.290 --> 01:22:50.760
inhibition.

1400
01:22:52.740 --> 01:22:55.420
We then asked the question of what is happening within these cells?

1401
01:22:55.800 --> 01:22:56.900
Why are they going away?

1402
01:22:58.080 --> 01:23:01.960
And so we assessed this by IHC, and even after three doses of

1403
01:23:02.200 --> 01:23:06.140
each of the RAS inhibitors, what we found is an elevation of cleaved caspase-3,

1404
01:23:06.580 --> 01:23:09.820
suggesting that these pre-malignant cells are undergoing cell death.

1405
01:23:10.520 --> 01:23:13.430
However, in addition to cell death, we also asked the question of whether or not

1406
01:23:13.500 --> 01:23:17.480
transdifferentiation was also contributing to the disappearance of these panin

1407
01:23:17.520 --> 01:23:20.800
lesions histologically. And we didn't find any evidence for this,

1408
01:23:21.400 --> 01:23:24.740
and this mirrors and is

1409
01:23:25.540 --> 01:23:29.400
consistent with the evidence from the inducible KRAS models that was published

1410
01:23:29.420 --> 01:23:30.560
almost over a decade ago.

1411
01:23:32.520 --> 01:23:34.780
And so we see that these precursor lesions are disappearing.

1412
01:23:35.240 --> 01:23:35.940
We then asked,

1413
01:23:36.780 --> 01:23:39.700
does this alter the natural history of PDAC?

1414
01:23:40.460 --> 01:23:44.020
And so we again took KPC mice, made sure that they did not have

1415
01:23:44.060 --> 01:23:47.900
tumors, exposed them to four weeks of RAS inhibition,

1416
01:23:49.060 --> 01:23:50.100
took them off therapy,

1417
01:23:51.180 --> 01:23:54.260
and then continued to monitor them for tumor development.

1418
01:23:55.100 --> 01:23:58.860
And so in mice, we can actually use high-resolution ultrasound to

1419
01:23:59.420 --> 01:24:02.200
diagnose tumors. This method is highly sensitive.

1420
01:24:02.300 --> 01:24:05.420
We're able to detect tumors as small as five to 10 cubic millimeters.

1421
01:24:07.620 --> 01:24:11.560
And what we found is that even four weeks of RAS inhibition alone is able

1422
01:24:11.620 --> 01:24:14.900
to significantly delay the onset of tumors within these mice.

1423
01:24:16.740 --> 01:24:20.620
And that delay in tumor onset also translates to

1424
01:24:20.660 --> 01:24:23.900
an overall survival benefit within these mice.

1425
01:24:23.910 --> 01:24:27.820
And so we have shown previously that T cells are an important part

1426
01:24:27.960 --> 01:24:31.520
of maintaining tumor control and RAS inhibition within

1427
01:24:31.540 --> 01:24:35.400
preclinical models of mice. So we asked the question of whether or not T cells were

1428
01:24:35.460 --> 01:24:36.500
also contributing

1429
01:24:37.960 --> 01:24:38.600
to this effect.

1430
01:24:39.480 --> 01:24:42.960
And so we repeated the same experiment, but during this iteration, we actually

1431
01:24:42.980 --> 01:24:46.740
depleted CD4 and CD8 T cells, both during RAS inhibition

1432
01:24:46.820 --> 01:24:48.810
and subsequently thereafter,

1433
01:24:50.080 --> 01:24:52.000
and then monitored again for tumor development.

1434
01:24:53.600 --> 01:24:57.380
Here I'm showing you the results from the prior experiment in the dotted

1435
01:24:57.420 --> 01:25:01.360
lines. And what we found is that when we deplete T cells, it actually

1436
01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:04.099
did not really influence the time to tumor onset,

1437
01:25:04.960 --> 01:25:08.740
nor the survival of these mice. And so from this, we concluded that

1438
01:25:09.120 --> 01:25:12.840
the T cells were not playing a role in the RAS inhibition interception

1439
01:25:12.880 --> 01:25:13.620
phenotype that we were

1440
01:25:13.640 --> 01:25:17.060
seeing.

1441
01:25:17.680 --> 01:25:20.600
And so we know that a defined amount of RAS inhibition

1442
01:25:22.520 --> 01:25:24.220
provides overall survival benefit.

1443
01:25:24.780 --> 01:25:28.670
We then hypothesized that if we go back in and intervene on panin again, that

1444
01:25:28.700 --> 01:25:29.880
this would provide

1445
01:25:31.140 --> 01:25:35.000
a more extended benefit. To perform this experiment, we again

1446
01:25:35.020 --> 01:25:38.960
took seven-week-old mice and exposed them to a week of RAS inhibition

1447
01:25:39.020 --> 01:25:42.980
every other week. So a week on of therapy and a week off of therapy, and monitored

1448
01:25:43.040 --> 01:25:47.010
them again for tumor development.And what we found was that

1449
01:25:47.040 --> 01:25:50.780
the strategy was highly effective in delaying the time to

1450
01:25:50.800 --> 01:25:54.340
tumor onset within these mice, delaying it by over 200 days.

1451
01:25:56.200 --> 01:25:58.820
And this raises an interesting question of whether or not

1452
01:25:59.660 --> 01:26:02.240
it makes sense to intervene earlier within this disease.

1453
01:26:03.900 --> 01:26:07.840
And so in order to assess this experimentally, what we did was we looked at the

1454
01:26:07.900 --> 01:26:11.820
survival of mice under this interception arm and compared

1455
01:26:11.840 --> 01:26:15.800
it to the survival of mice that received RAS inhibition after a

1456
01:26:15.900 --> 01:26:19.420
tumor had formerly developed, what I'm calling the treatment arm.

1457
01:26:20.200 --> 01:26:24.060
And what we found is that even we know that

1458
01:26:24.100 --> 01:26:27.360
RAS inhibition after a tumor develops provides benefit,

1459
01:26:28.100 --> 01:26:31.730
and in this experiment, we see that mice prolong their

1460
01:26:31.780 --> 01:26:35.540
survival by two months when you treat their tumors.

1461
01:26:37.820 --> 01:26:40.460
However, as you start and you eliminate pannens,

1462
01:26:41.540 --> 01:26:43.000
preventing tumors from forming,

1463
01:26:43.940 --> 01:26:47.440
you can actually extend overall survival by over a year in KPC mice.

1464
01:26:49.420 --> 01:26:53.300
This provides really strong evidence for interception within this

1465
01:26:53.360 --> 01:26:55.370
model over treatment.

1466
01:26:59.360 --> 01:27:02.160
And so we then asked the question of whether or not this is a class effect.

1467
01:27:02.400 --> 01:27:05.060
Can we use other RAS inhibitors to mimic the same effect?

1468
01:27:07.360 --> 01:27:10.850
And so again, we took KPC mice and exposed them to 10 days

1469
01:27:10.960 --> 01:27:14.660
of MRTX1133, which is a G12D

1470
01:27:14.720 --> 01:27:15.500
specific inhibitor.

1471
01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:20.900
And we actually found really profound sterilization of these

1472
01:27:20.980 --> 01:27:24.200
pannen lesions that was also confirmed in our 3D

1473
01:27:24.240 --> 01:27:25.000
reconstructions.

1474
01:27:27.080 --> 01:27:29.640
And then again asked the same question of whether or not we can

1475
01:27:31.080 --> 01:27:32.120
provide metronomic

1476
01:27:32.920 --> 01:27:36.340
dosing to eliminate pannens recurrently.

1477
01:27:37.420 --> 01:27:38.900
So similar to the prior experiment,

1478
01:27:40.160 --> 01:27:43.320
a week at a time, we gave RAS inhibition.

1479
01:27:43.360 --> 01:27:45.800
In this case, we gave it every three weeks instead of every other week

1480
01:27:47.340 --> 01:27:49.360
and found something quite similar.

1481
01:27:52.680 --> 01:27:56.530
And so I just want to comment that this experiment went on for so long that we had

1482
01:27:56.640 --> 01:27:59.360
to re-genotype a lot of these mice to make sure that they still had the RAS

1483
01:27:59.400 --> 01:28:03.340
allele. And the other thing that I'll point out is that the

1484
01:28:03.400 --> 01:28:07.109
oldest mouse in the study lived to about 600 days, which is

1485
01:28:07.140 --> 01:28:10.800
close to the lifespan of a KRAS

1486
01:28:10.860 --> 01:28:11.600
wild-type mouse.

1487
01:28:13.580 --> 01:28:15.760
And I think this is a testament to the

1488
01:28:16.700 --> 01:28:20.400
power and potential of cancer interception over treatment.

1489
01:28:22.060 --> 01:28:23.080
And so the key takeaways,

1490
01:28:24.820 --> 01:28:26.480
RAS inhibition can eliminate pannen.

1491
01:28:28.420 --> 01:28:32.340
If you eliminate pannen, you can delay tumor onset and prolong overall survival.

1492
01:28:34.040 --> 01:28:37.560
And if you intercept before you treat,

1493
01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:41.560
it may be easier to impede on

1494
01:28:41.600 --> 01:28:44.489
pre-cancer rather than trying to catch up to it later.

1495
01:28:45.570 --> 01:28:49.340
And so with that, I'd like to thank everyone

1496
01:28:49.380 --> 01:28:53.020
who's helped, Ben Stanger and Bob Vonderheide, as well as my funding

1497
01:28:53.040 --> 01:28:56.920
sources. And then I'm going to put in a pitch that I'm starting a lab in the

1498
01:28:56.960 --> 01:28:59.960
fall, so if you're interested in studying interception, send me an email.

1499
01:29:00.160 --> 01:29:02.960
I'm looking to hire and I'm looking for collaborators. Thanks.

1500
01:29:14.000 --> 01:29:14.560
Questions?

1501
01:29:18.120 --> 01:29:18.520
Over there.

1502
01:29:20.080 --> 01:29:20.220
Hi.

1503
01:29:21.640 --> 01:29:22.140
Great talk.

1504
01:29:23.560 --> 01:29:25.920
Also, the paper in "Science" is beautiful. Congratulations.

1505
01:29:25.940 --> 01:29:26.200
Thank you.

1506
01:29:27.560 --> 01:29:31.020
It's really hard in the clinics to catch early stage PDAC,

1507
01:29:31.560 --> 01:29:35.360
so let alone pannens. How do you see this coming

1508
01:29:35.420 --> 01:29:38.940
into translating into actual benefit of potentially targeting those pannens?

1509
01:29:39.750 --> 01:29:42.880
That's a great question. I think the patients that we need to look at are the

1510
01:29:42.900 --> 01:29:46.140
patients who are of highest risk for

1511
01:29:46.150 --> 01:29:49.220
developing pancreas cancer. And so when we look

1512
01:29:49.240 --> 01:29:53.080
across different studies, those patients could include those who

1513
01:29:53.140 --> 01:29:55.600
have high risk pancreatic cysts,

1514
01:29:56.440 --> 01:29:56.880
patients who

1515
01:29:58.000 --> 01:30:01.700
have germline predisposition syndromes, and then patients who also have clinical

1516
01:30:01.780 --> 01:30:05.000
features such as new onset diabetes or chronic

1517
01:30:05.019 --> 01:30:05.780
pancreatitis.

1518
01:30:08.019 --> 01:30:11.040
There's obviously a lot more that we need to study in this, but I think that's a

1519
01:30:11.060 --> 01:30:11.940
good starting point

1520
01:30:12.940 --> 01:30:15.540
to trying to figure out who's going to benefit from this type of study.

1521
01:30:16.300 --> 01:30:16.540
Thanks.

1522
01:30:19.780 --> 01:30:20.400
Wonderful job.

1523
01:30:21.640 --> 01:30:24.400
I'm wondering, when you are doing the

1524
01:30:25.260 --> 01:30:28.760
immune cell depletion during the drug treatment,

1525
01:30:29.300 --> 01:30:32.760
have you ever tried depletion of

1526
01:30:33.720 --> 01:30:37.360
other cell types, such as macrophages or fibroblasts, as we know that

1527
01:30:37.520 --> 01:30:40.740
pancreatic cancer is heavily related to these

1528
01:30:41.160 --> 01:30:42.700
fibroblasts? Yeah.

1529
01:30:43.620 --> 01:30:45.080
We have not done that experiment yet.

1530
01:30:45.140 --> 01:30:48.720
But what we do see is that we do see a decrease in macrophages with RAS

1531
01:30:48.780 --> 01:30:52.160
inhibition, and so I think that could potentially potentiate the effect,

1532
01:30:52.260 --> 01:30:52.890
but-

1533
01:30:53.300 --> 01:30:53.969
Okay. Thank you

1534
01:30:53.969 --> 01:30:54.700
... we haven't done that yet.

1535
01:30:57.880 --> 01:31:01.040
Because he took my question, I'm going to ask a different question.

1536
01:31:02.640 --> 01:31:05.560
I'm wondering whether you think,

1537
01:31:06.760 --> 01:31:07.920
to the room,

1538
01:31:08.980 --> 01:31:12.400
Niranjan was mentioning maybe we can do this KRAS

1539
01:31:12.480 --> 01:31:15.220
cleansing. And

1540
01:31:16.220 --> 01:31:19.940
based on what we know about KRAS mutations in pannen,

1541
01:31:21.200 --> 01:31:23.560
all of us are probably walking around with them.

1542
01:31:24.160 --> 01:31:27.980
So do you think that in the future, this could be even a

1543
01:31:28.020 --> 01:31:30.740
prevention for a general population?

1544
01:31:33.080 --> 01:31:35.180
Depends how far in the future do you want me to think?

1545
01:31:36.060 --> 01:31:36.660
But I think-

1546
01:31:37.180 --> 01:31:38.020
Be a dreamer.

1547
01:31:38.440 --> 01:31:39.380
Yeah. So I think

1548
01:31:40.760 --> 01:31:41.780
if we

1549
01:31:42.580 --> 01:31:45.540
look at what we're doing for primary prevention of cardiac disease,

1550
01:31:45.880 --> 01:31:49.116
right?Some people think statin should be in the

1551
01:31:49.136 --> 01:31:50.016
water.

1552
01:31:51.196 --> 01:31:54.286
I think the most important thing is actually safety of these drugs and tolerability

1553
01:31:54.316 --> 01:31:57.976
of these drugs. And so I think if we find a safe,

1554
01:31:58.076 --> 01:32:00.636
tolerable drug, then I think we can be dreamers.

1555
01:32:03.176 --> 01:32:05.116
Can I ask one question to follow up on that?

1556
01:32:05.516 --> 01:32:08.416
Because it's very hard to cure mice that are constantly getting new penance, and

1557
01:32:08.456 --> 01:32:10.475
your survival is amazing what you're getting there.

1558
01:32:11.476 --> 01:32:14.636
Do you think of developing a system where you're just getting a one-time incidence

1559
01:32:14.676 --> 01:32:18.036
of Cre recombination and see if you can just, and the question I've just asked,

1560
01:32:18.336 --> 01:32:21.556
come in one time, treat, and then never get cancer in those mice?

1561
01:32:21.776 --> 01:32:22.616
Yeah, I'm working on it.

1562
01:32:25.396 --> 01:32:26.036
All right, thank you.

1563
01:32:33.896 --> 01:32:36.516
So our last speaker is Dr. Wolpin,

1564
01:32:37.456 --> 01:32:38.736
and he'll be talking about

1565
01:32:39.636 --> 01:32:43.376
a clinical trial of nab-paclitaxel and

1566
01:32:44.436 --> 01:32:47.936
gemcitabine chemotherapy with deruxnaratib in the first line setting.

1567
01:32:49.316 --> 01:32:53.026
Excellent. Well, on behalf of my co-authors who you can see here,

1568
01:32:53.816 --> 01:32:57.366
just to thank the session organizers for the invitation to speak today.

1569
01:32:58.116 --> 01:33:01.956
So we're going to talk about today initial results from a clinical

1570
01:33:01.996 --> 01:33:05.436
trial evaluating deruxnaratib plus

1571
01:33:05.456 --> 01:33:09.436
chemotherapy in the first-line treatment of patients with

1572
01:33:09.496 --> 01:33:10.886
metastatic pancreatic cancer.

1573
01:33:12.396 --> 01:33:13.616
These are my disclosures.

1574
01:33:15.076 --> 01:33:18.656
So I think as this audience knows, and Haemin was just talking about,

1575
01:33:18.746 --> 01:33:20.676
pancreatic cancer is a very difficult disease.

1576
01:33:21.036 --> 01:33:24.916
So it often does present late, and we don't have nearly as

1577
01:33:24.996 --> 01:33:26.996
many treatment options as we would like.

1578
01:33:27.536 --> 01:33:31.376
And so currently in the first-line setting, for most patients with metastatic

1579
01:33:31.436 --> 01:33:34.126
pancreatic cancer, we use multi-agent chemotherapy.

1580
01:33:34.576 --> 01:33:38.136
And there are two basic programs we tend to use, either a gemcitabine-based

1581
01:33:38.216 --> 01:33:41.906
program or a 5-FU-based program. For the gemcitabine-based

1582
01:33:41.976 --> 01:33:44.856
programs, that's usually gemcitabine plus nab-paclitaxel.

1583
01:33:45.356 --> 01:33:48.836
And for the 5-FU-based programs, that's generally FOLFIRINOX or

1584
01:33:48.896 --> 01:33:52.456
NALIRIFOX. The efficacy data in that

1585
01:33:52.536 --> 01:33:56.356
setting has been historically, if you look across a number of different clinical

1586
01:33:56.396 --> 01:34:00.356
trials, a response rate in about the 30% to 40% range

1587
01:34:00.396 --> 01:34:03.976
for objective response rate, a median PFS in the five to

1588
01:34:04.056 --> 01:34:07.896
seven-month range, and median OS in the nine to 12-month

1589
01:34:07.996 --> 01:34:11.396
range. So this really does leave a lot to be desired, much

1590
01:34:11.456 --> 01:34:14.456
improvements that we can try to identify.

1591
01:34:15.256 --> 01:34:18.985
And it turns out, as was just discussed, that over 90% of

1592
01:34:19.056 --> 01:34:22.896
pancreas cancers carry an activating oncogenic mutation in RAS.

1593
01:34:23.356 --> 01:34:27.296
And so this really provides us an opportunity to target this as

1594
01:34:27.366 --> 01:34:31.076
a novel therapeutic approach for patients with metastatic pancreatic cancer.

1595
01:34:32.976 --> 01:34:35.436
So the drug we'll talk about today is deruxnaratib.

1596
01:34:35.736 --> 01:34:39.116
It's an oral potent RAS on multi-selective

1597
01:34:39.316 --> 01:34:43.116
non-covalent inhibitor. It targets GTP, so

1598
01:34:43.216 --> 01:34:47.076
active on state RAS at codons 12,

1599
01:34:47.176 --> 01:34:50.556
13, and 61, as well as wild-type RAS.

1600
01:34:51.156 --> 01:34:54.796
And it enters the cell, binds to cyclophilin A to form a binary

1601
01:34:54.896 --> 01:34:58.336
complex, which then binds to GTP-bound RAS

1602
01:34:58.856 --> 01:35:02.316
and sterically hinders the ability of effector proteins to bind to

1603
01:35:02.356 --> 01:35:06.276
GTP-bound RAS, and then suppresses downstream

1604
01:35:06.356 --> 01:35:10.296
signaling. So the reason for this trial, which is a first-line

1605
01:35:10.336 --> 01:35:14.016
clinical trial, was data that was coming from patients who had been previously

1606
01:35:14.056 --> 01:35:17.846
treated. So a previous clinical trial, Phase I, II study, had

1607
01:35:17.856 --> 01:35:21.436
demonstrated that in second line and beyond, deruxnaratib had a

1608
01:35:21.476 --> 01:35:25.076
manageable safety profile and substantial clinical

1609
01:35:25.136 --> 01:35:27.196
activity. And that prompted the current study.

1610
01:35:28.816 --> 01:35:32.296
So the study that we'll talk about is called the GI102

1611
01:35:32.356 --> 01:35:36.236
platform study. This is actually a larger study that involves

1612
01:35:36.256 --> 01:35:39.816
RAS on inhibitors in different combinations across GI

1613
01:35:39.856 --> 01:35:43.496
cancers. We're going to talk today about sub-protocol C,

1614
01:35:43.896 --> 01:35:47.386
which is a protocol specifically for patients with metastatic

1615
01:35:47.456 --> 01:35:49.936
pancreatic cancer that has not been previously treated.

1616
01:35:50.376 --> 01:35:54.076
So this is a first line study, and it combines deruxnaratib

1617
01:35:54.116 --> 01:35:56.676
plus gemcitabine and nab-paclitaxel.

1618
01:35:56.716 --> 01:35:59.196
You can see to the left the eligibility criteria.

1619
01:35:59.656 --> 01:36:02.996
I think really the key here again is that this is a first-line study, so patients

1620
01:36:03.016 --> 01:36:06.985
were not allowed to have received systemic therapy previously for

1621
01:36:06.996 --> 01:36:10.856
their metastatic disease. There were two dose escalation cohorts, dose

1622
01:36:10.916 --> 01:36:14.616
level 1A and 1B. Both of these cohorts involved

1623
01:36:14.836 --> 01:36:18.236
deruxnaratib at 200 milligrams orally once daily.

1624
01:36:18.956 --> 01:36:22.456
In dose level 1A, gemcitabine and nab-paclitaxel was given in its

1625
01:36:22.576 --> 01:36:26.496
standard form, so days one, eight, and 15 on a 28-day

1626
01:36:26.596 --> 01:36:30.316
cycle. And in 1B, it was given on day one and day 15,

1627
01:36:30.356 --> 01:36:33.516
dropping day eight, again on a 28-day cycle.

1628
01:36:33.596 --> 01:36:37.156
After review of data from initial patients enrolled to the two dose

1629
01:36:37.276 --> 01:36:40.856
levels, dose level 1B was chosen as the dose expansion.

1630
01:36:41.596 --> 01:36:45.276
You can see the objectives were safety tolerability as the primary objective.

1631
01:36:45.676 --> 01:36:49.096
Secondary objectives were anti-tumor activity and exploratory

1632
01:36:49.156 --> 01:36:51.836
objectives around molecular response using ctDNA.

1633
01:36:52.396 --> 01:36:55.815
The data we'll present is from dose level 1B from the dose

1634
01:36:55.876 --> 01:36:59.466
escalation backfill dose expansion, so 40

1635
01:36:59.556 --> 01:37:01.236
patients total that we'll talk about.

1636
01:37:02.856 --> 01:37:06.176
So these are the demographics and the baseline characteristics for these 40

1637
01:37:06.196 --> 01:37:10.185
patients. You can see the median age is around 70 years, very common for

1638
01:37:10.256 --> 01:37:13.986
pancreatic cancer. About half and half men and women, and

1639
01:37:14.056 --> 01:37:17.796
ECOG performance zero and one. 70% of patients had liver

1640
01:37:17.806 --> 01:37:20.956
metastases, again, very common in this setting.

1641
01:37:20.976 --> 01:37:24.916
And some patients had had prior surgery, but all patients had metastatic disease

1642
01:37:24.956 --> 01:37:26.576
at the time of enrollment to the study.

1643
01:37:27.566 --> 01:37:29.816
And then you can see to the right the RAS genotypes.

1644
01:37:29.976 --> 01:37:33.416
So 50% of patients had G12D mutations in KRAS,

1645
01:37:34.076 --> 01:37:37.816
25% had G12V, 18% G12R, three

1646
01:37:37.896 --> 01:37:39.436
patients had other mutant alleles.

1647
01:37:39.776 --> 01:37:43.676
This again is very common, a very common distribution for what we see in

1648
01:37:43.716 --> 01:37:45.556
terms of RAS mutant alleles in pancreatic

1649
01:37:45.616 --> 01:37:49.284
cancer.So to start with the safety.

1650
01:37:49.544 --> 01:37:53.114
So this is safety tolerability of duraxonrasib plus gemcitabine and

1651
01:37:53.144 --> 01:37:56.784
nab-paclitaxel. These are the treatment-related adverse events by

1652
01:37:56.824 --> 01:38:00.664
CTCAE grading. You can see to the left, in the left column is any

1653
01:38:00.704 --> 01:38:04.514
grade, and to the right is grade three or greater

1654
01:38:04.744 --> 01:38:08.544
adverse events. You can see in the any grade column, the most

1655
01:38:08.564 --> 01:38:11.744
common adverse event was rash, which we have seen before with

1656
01:38:11.764 --> 01:38:15.344
duraxonrasib, with the vast majority of patients getting some rash.

1657
01:38:15.884 --> 01:38:17.884
For most patients, this was low-grade rash.

1658
01:38:18.144 --> 01:38:22.084
Again, usually now we've seen across studies about 10% to 15%

1659
01:38:22.124 --> 01:38:26.004
of patients get a grade three or higher rash, and it was similar in this study.

1660
01:38:26.044 --> 01:38:29.804
If you focus on the grade three or greater column, the toxicities that you

1661
01:38:29.824 --> 01:38:33.224
see are essentially the toxicities that we know when you look at

1662
01:38:33.264 --> 01:38:36.364
duraxonrasib individually, when you look at chemotherapy individually.

1663
01:38:36.744 --> 01:38:40.584
There were not new safety signals, but you could see, again, adverse events as you

1664
01:38:40.604 --> 01:38:44.584
would expect from both of these drugs, or really three drugs,

1665
01:38:44.844 --> 01:38:47.124
because two chemotherapy agents at the same time.

1666
01:38:49.044 --> 01:38:52.523
So if we then look at what led to dose modifications and how many dose

1667
01:38:52.564 --> 01:38:56.424
modifications there were among the 40 patients, I'll highlight a few of these

1668
01:38:56.464 --> 01:38:59.624
numbers. If you look at dose reduction, you can see

1669
01:38:59.824 --> 01:39:03.484
35% of patients needed a dose reduction in duraxonrasib,

1670
01:39:03.884 --> 01:39:07.724
and 58% of patients needed a dose reduction in gem

1671
01:39:07.744 --> 01:39:11.554
nab-paclitaxel. If you look at dose discontinuation, about

1672
01:39:11.924 --> 01:39:15.694
5% of patients discontinued duraxonrasib because of

1673
01:39:15.694 --> 01:39:18.924
toxicity, and 15% of chemotherapy.

1674
01:39:19.404 --> 01:39:22.204
Again, chemotherapy does carry with it significant side effects.

1675
01:39:22.244 --> 01:39:25.764
We do see discontinuations of chemotherapy in normal practice.

1676
01:39:26.464 --> 01:39:30.384
And you can see the mean and the median dose intensity for the duraxonrasib

1677
01:39:30.584 --> 01:39:33.524
and for the chemotherapy was between 80% and 90%.

1678
01:39:35.484 --> 01:39:39.044
If we then look at the efficacy for duraxonrasib plus gemcitabine and

1679
01:39:39.064 --> 01:39:42.884
nab-paclitaxel, you see to the left the waterfall plot with a sizable

1680
01:39:42.964 --> 01:39:46.244
number of patients having substantial reductions in tumor burden.

1681
01:39:46.984 --> 01:39:50.004
If you look in the table on the right, the objective response rate was

1682
01:39:50.184 --> 01:39:54.104
58%. This is the confirmed ORR. And you can see the

1683
01:39:54.124 --> 01:39:56.444
disease control rate was 90%.

1684
01:39:57.263 --> 01:40:01.024
If you look at landmark times for PFS and OS at

1685
01:40:01.084 --> 01:40:04.714
six months, you see 84% of patients had

1686
01:40:04.944 --> 01:40:08.824
a landmark six-month PFS and 90% of patients six-month

1687
01:40:08.924 --> 01:40:12.764
landmark OS. We were unable to calculate median PFS and

1688
01:40:12.844 --> 01:40:16.694
OS because there were not enough events yet to calculate a stable estimate for the

1689
01:40:16.744 --> 01:40:17.224
medians.

1690
01:40:19.364 --> 01:40:22.944
If we then look at the ctDNA as a marker of molecular response,

1691
01:40:23.444 --> 01:40:26.204
we had 28 patients where this was possible of the 40.

1692
01:40:26.624 --> 01:40:30.164
These 28 patients required a pre-treatment blood sample with a

1693
01:40:30.204 --> 01:40:33.044
measurable RAS allele, a K RAS allele that we could measure.

1694
01:40:33.634 --> 01:40:36.904
And then they needed to have a second blood sample collected either cycle two, day

1695
01:40:36.944 --> 01:40:40.444
one or cycle three, day one, where we also could measure

1696
01:40:40.484 --> 01:40:43.844
ctDNA. What you could see on the left is the

1697
01:40:43.904 --> 01:40:47.744
reduction in ctDNA or ctDNA RAS variant

1698
01:40:47.804 --> 01:40:51.064
allele fraction between the pre and the on-treatment samples.

1699
01:40:51.564 --> 01:40:55.544
And then if you look to the right, what you can see is 96% of patients at

1700
01:40:55.604 --> 01:40:59.444
a 50% or greater decrease in ctDNA RAS

1701
01:40:59.464 --> 01:41:03.234
variant allele fraction, and 61% had complete

1702
01:41:03.284 --> 01:41:06.544
clearance of ctDNA where the RAS mutation was no longer

1703
01:41:06.904 --> 01:41:08.264
identifiable in the blood.

1704
01:41:10.164 --> 01:41:12.484
So if we ask what are the summaries and conclusions?

1705
01:41:12.824 --> 01:41:16.064
So the summaries and conclusions from this initial study of 40 patients

1706
01:41:16.084 --> 01:41:19.904
receiving duraxonrasib and gemcitabine nab-paclitaxel

1707
01:41:19.944 --> 01:41:23.734
as first-line treatment showed a manageable safety profile with

1708
01:41:23.764 --> 01:41:27.544
consistent toxicities of what we know from the drugs from prior

1709
01:41:27.664 --> 01:41:31.504
studies at a mean and median dose intensity between 80% and

1710
01:41:31.704 --> 01:41:34.764
90% across patients and across the study.

1711
01:41:35.553 --> 01:41:39.464
The combination demonstrated compelling initial evidence of activity

1712
01:41:39.504 --> 01:41:43.404
with an objective response rate of 58% and a disease

1713
01:41:43.464 --> 01:41:47.364
control rate of 90%. In addition, there was some early evidence

1714
01:41:47.424 --> 01:41:51.084
of durability of this response with a six-month landmark

1715
01:41:51.124 --> 01:41:54.764
PFS of 84% and an OS of 90%.

1716
01:41:55.024 --> 01:41:58.904
Again, as reference, a landmark of PFS in chemotherapy in the

1717
01:41:58.944 --> 01:42:01.654
first line setting is about 50% from larger trials.

1718
01:42:02.884 --> 01:42:06.424
Early on-treatment clearance of ctDNA was seen in almost two-thirds of

1719
01:42:06.464 --> 01:42:10.144
patients. And these data, along

1720
01:42:10.184 --> 01:42:13.964
with other pieces of data, have now led to

1721
01:42:14.104 --> 01:42:18.024
an opening and an initial enrollment of the Resolute 303 trial, which

1722
01:42:18.064 --> 01:42:21.824
is a phase three clinical trial, and the next slide will show the

1723
01:42:21.884 --> 01:42:25.844
schema of that. I would also point you to and draw your attention to an

1724
01:42:25.924 --> 01:42:29.644
abstract that's being presented now actually at the poster session by Dr.

1725
01:42:29.824 --> 01:42:33.764
Eileen O'Reilly. This abstract is looking again at a first-line setting

1726
01:42:33.804 --> 01:42:37.284
for patients with metastatic pancreatic cancer, and that abstract looking at

1727
01:42:37.304 --> 01:42:39.824
duraxonrasib alone, not with chemotherapy.

1728
01:42:41.684 --> 01:42:45.604
So this is the design of the study that's now open and enrolling the Resolute

1729
01:42:45.664 --> 01:42:49.624
303 study. Again, if you look to the left for the eligibility, these are patients

1730
01:42:49.664 --> 01:42:51.324
with metastatic pancreatic cancer.

1731
01:42:51.864 --> 01:42:54.604
No prior treatment for their metastatic disease is allowed.

1732
01:42:55.054 --> 01:42:58.884
And these patients are randomized to one of three different arms, either

1733
01:42:58.904 --> 01:43:02.594
duraxonrasib alone, duraxonrasib plus gemcitabine and

1734
01:43:02.604 --> 01:43:05.794
nab-paclitaxel, or as the standard arm gemcitabine and

1735
01:43:05.824 --> 01:43:09.364
nab-paclitaxel. And you can see a joint primary endpoint of

1736
01:43:09.404 --> 01:43:10.964
PFS and OS.

1737
01:43:12.074 --> 01:43:15.944
So I'd just like to acknowledge the many patients who contributed to these

1738
01:43:15.984 --> 01:43:19.764
data, the families who supported them through their treatment, the

1739
01:43:19.804 --> 01:43:23.564
clinical investigators, and the staff who helped take care of them, the Revolution

1740
01:43:23.624 --> 01:43:26.904
Medicines team, and then all of you for your attention. So thank you very much.

